[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.04.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Url "https://www.chessable.com/variation/20488270"]
[ECO "D15"]

1. d4 d5
2. c4 c6
3. Nf3 Nf6
4. Nc3 e6
5. g3 {Hello everyone and welcome to my very first Chessable course! My name is Sipke Ernst and I am a GM from the Netherlands. Although I am still reasonably active as a chess player, nowadays I am mainly working as a chess coach and I occasionally travel to tournaments as a second for my countryman Jorden van Foreest. That's enough about me for now and let's delve into what this course is about. The Semi-Slav is a very reliable weapon for Black against 1.d4. Sam Shankland has made an excellent Chessable course on it in 2020, showing how incredibly difficult it is for White to get an advantage (if any advantage at all) in the sharp main lines that ensue after 5.Bg5 or 5.e3 . 

 When I was working as a second for Jorden during the Grand Swiss in Riga 2021, for his game against the strong Armenian GM Robert Hovhannisyan, we expected the Semi-Slav to come on the board and we decided to have a closer look at the move 5.g3!? At that point, I thought that White was mainly just taking some risk by sacrificing the pawn on c4, but after having studied it deeply with the help of the strongest engines, the line really started to grow on me. 

 For as far as we know, this move appeared in tournament practice for the first time in a game in 1936 between the strongest female player at that time, Vera Menchik, against the Czechoslovakian player Karel Treybal. Since then, it remained an irregular guest in tournament practice until the 90s, when the line was picked up by Topalov, although not with much success. 

 The title of the main contributor to the development of the line, however, belongs to Oleg Romanishin, who likes to put a bishop on g2 against pretty much whatever Black plays. In more recent years, this line has been played occasionally by nearly every world-class player, although mainly as a surprise weapon. The biggest experts nowadays are probably Daniil Dubov and Dmitry Andreikin. 

 Like in any other reliable opening, Black is equalizing with precise play, but that is only of academic interest. What White is aiming for is a position that poses practical problems for Black even when the evaluation by the strong engines is 0.00. 

 What is White trying to do by putting the bishop on g2? This line essentially is a gambit as in the critical lines, Black is going to be up one pawn (or more!) for a long time. After a subsequent ...dxc4, the bishop on g2 will exert a great deal of pressure on Black's queenside. I believe that if Black refrains from taking the pawn on c4, White has good chances for an advantage. In that case, the bishop on g2 helps to establish the desired e4-break, and after the position has opened up, White usually has the more active position. 

 Back to Riga 2021: Jorden played an excellent game and got a winning advantage, but lost it after a tragic blunder. Still, when back home, I decided to work on the line more and I started playing it in blitz. Since then, I have been waiting to play this opening in my first tournament game, and I finally got the chance in June 2022. That game can be found in the model games section as well and, although far from perfect, I think there is plenty to take away from it.}


