1. d4 d5
2. c4 c6
3. Nf3 Nf6
4. Nc3 e6
5. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf1g2]} Nbd7
6. Bg2 {This is the correct move order.} Be7 {Now we have a Closed Catalan. This is a rather passive line for Black so I think we should be happy if our opponents choose this line.

In the mainline of the Closed Catalan, the knight often goes to d2 (from where it defends c4 and supports e2-e4) but with the knight on c3 White also has good chances for an advantage. We are going to prepare the e2-e4 break and simultaneously try to make it hard for Black to get in ...c6-c5. 6...dxc4 transposes to the next chapters, whereas 6...Bd6 7.Nd2! transposes to<a class="commentMoveSmall" href="/course/115577/1" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-tippy-content="Link to chapter">the previous chapter.</a>}
7. Qd3 $5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ge2e4,Gd3e4,Gd3c4]} {It might look clumsy to defend the pawn on c4 like this, but it works. The queen also helps the e2-e4 advance.} b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} {I think this is a decent move. Black delays castling and starts to fight White's center straight away.}
8. e4 Ba6
9. b3 {[%csl Rc4]} {The pin on the c4-pawn looks uncomfortable for White but Black has difficulties increasing the pressure.} Bb4 {Forcing White's hand in the center.}
10. exd5 cxd5 {White also remains slightly better after 10...exd5 11.O-O O-O and now the simplest is 12.a3 and after Black's bishop retreat 12...Bd6 or 12...Be7 White can follow up with 13.Nh4 opening the long diagonal and aiming at the f5-square.}
11. O-O Rc8 {White has a good way to counter this.}
12. Nb5 Bxb5
13. cxb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f4,Gc1b2,Ga1c1,Gc1c6]} {With a slight advantage. White enjoys more space and can try to exploit the c6-square.}


