4. Nc3 e6
5. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf1g2]} dxc4
{There is an alternative for White here that Black can avoid by going 5...Nbd7 first, in which case we transpose to<a class="commentMoveSmall" href="/course/115577/2" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-tippy-content="Link to chapter">the Catalan chapter.</a>} 6. Bg2 {6.Ne5 has been played by Carlsen and Dubov but I don't see where is the fun for White when Black replies 6...Nbd7 7.Nxc4 b5 and no matter where the knight goes to me it looks like Black has easy play.} Bb4 {This move is inviting us to transpose to a line of the Catalan with 7.Ne5 . I think we can do better. Instead, 6...Be7?! might look normal but is a mistake nonetheless. White gets to pick up the pawn without any hassle. After 7.Ne5 Black can't defend the c4-pawn anymore with ...b7-b5. 7...O-O 8.Nxc4 We have the type of position that could come from a Catalan via the following move order: "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1" 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.g3 d5 4.Nf3 Be7 5.Bg2 O-O 6.Nc3 dxc4 7.Ne5 when instead of 7...c5 , 7...Nc6 or 7...Qd6 Black had played 7...c6?! 8.Nxc4⩲ . The bishop on g2 is a great piece and even if Black manages someday to play ...c5 then White will be much more actively placed so a symmetrical pawn structure does not guarantee a safe game for Black at all.}
7. a3 $5 {Forcing Black to make a decision with the bishop.} Bxc3+ {After this, White has the bishop pair and easy play.}
8. bxc3 O-O
9. a4 $1 {[%cal Gc1a3,Rb7b5]} {I'll show you a possible continuation.} Qa5 {[%csl Rc3]}
10. Qc2 Qf5 {[%cal Gf5c2]}
11. Qa2 {[%csl Rc4]} Nbd7
12. O-O e5 {Here White can strike in the center.}
13. e4 $1 {[%csl Rf5]} {The pawn is untouchable.} Nxe4
14. Qb1 {[%csl Re4,Rf5][%cal Gb1h7,Gf3h4,Gg2e4]} {Threatening 14...-- 15.Nh4 .} Nd6
15. Ba3 $18 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga3f8,Gd4e5]} {White is winning material.}


