1. d4 d5
2. c4 c6
3. Nf3 Nf6
4. Nc3 {Of course, White should also be prepared for other Slav variations such as 4...dxc4 or 4...a6 , which are out of the scope of this course.} e6 {This is the starting position of the Semi-Slav, a very reliable opening for Black. Now the main ways for White to try to get an advantage are 5.Bg5 and 5.e3 .

However, both these moves require you to memorize a great amount of theory in order to successfully play these lines and it remains uncertain whether you are really able to create real problems for an opponent who knows their main lines. White can look at one of the alternatives but most of them are hardly testing. All but one...}
5. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf1g2]} {I believe White can pose some problems to Black with this move. As far as we know, this move was played for the first time in 1936 by the strongest female player at that time, Vera Menchik, in a game against the Czechoslovakian player Karel Treybal.

In the 90s of the previous century, the line was picked up by Topalov, although not with much success. The title of the main contributor to the development of the line however belongs to Oleg Romanishin, about whom we know he likes to put a bishop on g2 against mostly whatever Black plays.

In more recent years, this line has been played by pretty much every world-class player once in a while, although mainly as a surprise weapon. The biggest experts nowadays are probably Dubov and Andreikin.

Like in any other opening, Black is equalizing with precise play. What White is aiming for is a position that poses practical problems for Black even when the evaluation by the strong engines is 0.00.

What is White trying to do by putting the bishop on g2? This line is essentially a gambit, as in the critical lines Black is going to be up a pawn (or more!) for a long time. After a subsequent ...dxc4, the bishop on g2 will exert a great deal of pressure on Black's queenside.

I believe that if Black refrains from taking the pawn on c4, we have good chances for an advantage. In that case, the bishop on g2 helps to establish the desired e4-break and after the position is opened up White usually has the more active position.} Bd6 $6 {[%csl Rd6]} {That saying 'knights should develop before the bishops' definitely applies here. The bishop on d6 is an easy target in this position, as the following lines illustrate:}
6. Bg2 dxc4 {This runs into problems due to the unfortunate position of Black's bishop.}
7. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gh1a8,Gd2c4]} {The bishop is completely misplaced on d6. If the bishop were on e7 Black could take on d4. After White takes on c4, Black has to move the bishop again or allow White to grab the bishop pair.} O-O {7...b5? runs into 8.Nxb5!± . We see the g2-bishop is powerful and the d6-bishop is exposed.}
8. Nxc4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d6]} {White is much better.}


