19. d5 Bxd5
20. Bxd5 exd5
21. e6 {Now Black has to return the piece. Here is the best way to do so:} Kb7
22. exd7 Qxd7 {[%csl Gc4,Gc5,Gd5]} {White is now up an exchange for a pawn but Black's central pawn mass counts for something. White should continue to play for the initiative.}
23. f5 {[%cal Gg5e6]} d4 {[%cal Gd4d3]} {That's a scary d-pawn!}
24. Ne6 Bd6 {Trading on e6 would be helpful to White.}
25. Qh5 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh5g4,Gh2h4]} {Taking on g7 is possible as well, but I prefer to play with queens on the board. Once again the engine’s verdict is 0.00. Still, the position is full of life and remains sharp. White is an exchange up but Black's pawn mass looks impressive. I would pick White in this position, but this is just a matter of taste.}


