1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 d5
4. Nc3 Be7 {Normally, the move order to reach the position in the game would be 4...c6 5.g3 Nbd7 6.Bg2 Be7 7.Qd3 O-O 8.O-O b6 .}
5. g3 O-O
6. Bg2 c6
7. O-O Nbd7
8. b3 b6
9. Qd3 Ba6
10. e4 Rc8 $6 {For some reason, this is the most popular move for Black in this position, but I believe it gives White an easy route to a big advantage. 10...dxc4 11.bxc4 e5 is critical and discussed in the chapter on the <a class="commentMoveSmall" href="/variation/18593001/#/11/b" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-tippy-content="Link to variation">Catalan</a>.}
11. Rd1 {Maybe even stronger is 11.e5!? Ne8 12.Rd1 Nc7 13.a4± when Black's position looks cramped. An attempt to break in the center straight away with 13...c5 would lead to even bigger problems after 14.dxc5! Nxc5 15.Qb1 Qe8 16.Nb5± .} dxc4 $6 {A better try is 11...dxe4 12.Nxe4 b5 13.Nxf6+ Bxf6 14.Be3⩲ .}
12. bxc4 b5 {Note that it is too late now for 12...e5?? 13.dxe5 Ng4 as it blunders a piece to 14.Qxd7 . 12...c5? 13.d5+- is awful for Black as well. The bishop on a6 is pointless now that Black is unable to challenge White's center.}
13. cxb5 cxb5 $2 {This releases the control over the d5-square. Maybe Black should consider 13...Bxb5 , although, if this is the best move, then clearly something has gone wrong. White is much better after 14.Nxb5 cxb5 15.Bh3!}
14. e5 $18 {[%csl Rd5]} Rxc3 {14...Nd5 15.Nxd5 exd5 − this structure is already quite bad for Black; White's majority on the kingside is very dangerous. Moreover, Black's bishop on a6 is misplaced and unprotected, and White can now make use of that with 16.a4 Qb6 17.Bf1+- .}
15. Qxc3 Nd5
16. Qb3 {White is an exchange up. True, Black has some squares, but it is no way enough to compensate for the material deficit and the strong Romanian GM quickly converts.} N7b6
17. Bf1 Nc4
18. a4 $1 {Opening up the game before Black can consolidate a bit.} Na5
19. Qd3 Nb4
20. Qb1 Bb7
21. Bg2 {21.d5!? Nxd5 22.axb5+-} Qa8
22. Ng5 Bxg5
23. Bxb7 Qxb7
24. Qxb4 Bd8
25. Ba3


