14. Nce4 Qc7 $2 {[%csl Rc7]} {This move looks quite logical, but loses on the spot! The queen is misplaced on c7 and the sacrifices on e6 will gain in strength. It was clear that the nowadays strong Danish GM didn't have a repertoire against our line of the Semi-Slav and likely was already improvising. The <a class="commentMoveSmall" href="/variation/18593180/#/14/b" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-tippy-content="Link to variation">mainline</a> continues with 14...h6 .}
15. Re1 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ge5d6]} Nf8 {[%csl Ge6]} {This protects e6, but now Black's kingside cannot be defended anymore. A) 15...h6? loses to 16.Nxe6! fxe6 17.Nd6+ Bxd6 18.exd6 and White wins a vital tempo because the black queen is now attacked. After 18...Qd8 ( 18...Qxd6 19.Rxe6+ ) "r2qk2r/pb1n4/2pPp1pp/1p1n4/2pP4/6PQ/PP3PBP/R1B1R1K1 w kq - 1 19" 19.Rxe6+ Kf7 20.Bxd5 cxd5 21.Bf4+- White is cruising to victory. B) 15...O-O-O ? is still not possible because of 16.Nxf7 . C) Relatively best was 15...N7b6 , although here White can deal out a serious blow with 16.Nd6+ Bxd6 17.exd6 Qd7 ( 17...Qxd6 loses to 18.Nxe6 ) "r3k2r/pb1q1p1p/1npPp1p1/1p1n2N1/2pP4/6PQ/PP3PBP/R1B1R1K1 w kq - 1 18" 18.Ne4+- when Black has lost all the grip on the dark squares. D) 15...Qb6 was seen in a game between Sunye Neto and Petursson in 1990, which must have been one of the first games in this line at the GM level. White continued with 16.Nd6+ Bxd6 17.exd6 and Black couldn't find anything better than 17...O-O-O , allowing 18.Nxf7+- .}
16. Qh6 $18 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gh6g7]} {Threatening to win a rook with Qg7.} Rg8
17. Bd2 {[%csl Rf7]} Qb6
18. Nc5 {Once again, we see that White doesn't mind giving a pawn on c5 this way.} Rd8 {18...Bxc5 19.dxc5 Qc7 ( 19...Qxc5 20.Ne4 ) "r3knr1/pbq2p1p/2p1p1pQ/1pPnP1N1/2p5/6P1/PP1B1PBP/R3R1K1 w q - 1 20" 20.Ne4 is a total disaster.}
19. Nge4 {[%csl Rd6,Rf6][%cal Gd2g5]} f5
20. exf6 Nxf6
21. Ba5 {Also strong is 21.Nxf6+ Bxf6 22.Nxe6 Nxe6 23.Rxe6+ Kf7 24.Rxf6+ Kxf6 25.Re1 and Black gets mated soon.} Qxa5
